={
"data": [
{
"id": 6558,
"documentId": "hwe0dxny0jypy8q9fij4tolg",
"title": "قال عليه السلام كن في الفتنة كٱبن اللَّبُون لا ظهرٌ فيُركب ولا ضَرعٌ فيُحلَب.",
"slug": "first-aphorism-in-sayings-chapter",
"type": "Saying",
"availableTranslations": null,
"createdAt": "2025-09-11T18:00:50.551Z",
"updatedAt": "2025-09-11T18:00:50.551Z",
"publishedAt": "2025-09-11T18:00:50.563Z",
"translations": [
{
"text": "In times of sedition, be like a young camel buck—no back to be ridden, no udders to be milked.",
"type": "en"
}
],
"sermonNumber": "3.1",
"heading": "First aphorism in Sayings chapter",
"footnotes": [
{
"id": 1586,
"documentId": "n4azhykoyzrgzw8ggmevopfi",
"number": "793",
"section": "3.1",
"arabic_word": "",
"english_word": "milked.",
"arabic_interpretation": "",
"english_translation": "Ar. ibn al-labūn, lit. “the son of a lactating camel mare,” referring to a buck that has just reached two years of age–his mother has had another foal and is again producing milk–he has no udders because he’s male and his back is weak because he’s young. ʿAlī advises his followers to be shrewd in times of conflict, so that despotic rulers are not able to harness their support for evil acts or bully them (Ḥ 18:82; B 935; R 3:267; F 397). From ʿAlī’s counsel to his son Ḥasan (Majlisī, Biḥār, 74:234).",
"createdAt": "2025-09-11T18:11:36.042Z",
"updatedAt": "2025-09-11T18:11:36.042Z",
"publishedAt": "2025-09-11T18:11:36.069Z"
}
],
"paragraphs": []
},
{
"id": 6560,
"documentId": "lsdpsmtd7u00hge2ocmznmo0",
"title": "وقال عليه السلام أَزرى بنفسه من ٱستشعر الطَّمَع ورضي بالذلّ من كشف ضرّه وهانت عليه نفسه من أمّر عليها لسانه. والبخل عارٌ والجبن مَنقصة والفقر يُخرس الفَطِن عن حجّته والمُقِلّ غريب في بلدته. والعجز آفة والصبر شجاعة والزهد ثروة والورع جُنّة ونعم القرين الرضى. والعلم وراثة كريمة والآداب حُلَل مُجدّدة والفكر مِرآة صافية. وصدر العاقل صُندوق سرّه. والبَشاشة حِبالة المودّة والاحتمال قبر العيوب. وروي أنّه عليه السلام قال في العبارة عن هذا المعنى أيضًا <المُسالمَة خَبء العيوب>. ومن رضي عن نفسه كثر الساخط عليه. والصدقة دواء مُنجِح. وأعمال العباد في عاجلهم نَصْبَ أَعيُنهم في آجلهم.",
"slug": "to-wear-the-robe-of-greed-is-to-degrade-yourself",
"type": "Saying",
"availableTranslations": null,
"createdAt": "2025-09-11T18:00:51.010Z",
"updatedAt": "2025-09-11T18:00:51.010Z",
"publishedAt": "2025-09-11T18:00:51.044Z",
"translations": [
{
"text": "To wear the robe of greed is to degrade yourself. To reveal your troubles to others is to humiliate yourself. To let your tongue control you is to demean yourself. Stinginess is a vice, cowardice is a defect, poverty strikes a clever man dumb, and a pauper is an exile in his hometown. Incapacity is a calamity, forbearance is a form of courage, renunciation is a treasure, restraint is a shield, and acceptance of God’s will is the best companion. Knowledge is a noble legacy, refined behavior is like new clothing, and thought is a polished mirror. A wise man’s heart is a vault for his secrets. Cheerfulness is a snare for friendship, forbearance is a tomb for shortcomings. Raḍī: It is also narrated that ʿAlī said similarly: Conciliation is a tomb for flaws. The smug invite detractors. Almsgiving is powerful medicine. Believers’ deeds in this world will be placed before them in the hereafter.",
"type": "en"
}
],
"sermonNumber": "3.2",
"heading": "To wear the robe of greed is to degrade yourself.",
"footnotes": [
{
"id": 1588,
"documentId": "h5lez8e9fsdvamd405geflak",
"number": "794",
"section": "3.2",
"arabic_word": "",
"english_word": "yourself",
"arabic_interpretation": "",
"english_translation": "The sayings in §3.2 are from ʿAlī’s counsel to Ashtar. Ḥarrānī, Tuḥaf, 201-202.",
"createdAt": "2025-09-11T18:11:36.484Z",
"updatedAt": "2025-09-11T18:11:36.484Z",
"publishedAt": "2025-09-11T18:11:36.510Z"
}
],
"paragraphs": []
},
{
